ding if or how they would work as a system, and then scaling that loose con=
stellation up before it had become something that people were willing to pa=
y for. Katerra tried to do too much, too soon. It=E2=80=99s possible to sta=
rt out too vertically integrated.
I share Katerra=E2=80=99s story not because it=E2=80=99s particularly uniqu=
e, and certainly not to demean the effort, but because, after two weeks of =
excitement about Vertical Integrators, I want to make it abundantly clear h=
ow hard it is to build them.=C2=A0
The default outcome for any startup is failure. It takes tremendous force o=
f will, execution, strategy, smarts, and luck to overcome very long odds. V=
ertical Integrators turn all of that difficulty up to 11.=C2=A0
Anil Varanasi runs Meter [ https://substack.com/redirect/db9cda00-27bd-4ba2=
-8efd-2fde9038b021?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], one of my favorite Verical Integrators, with his brother Suni=
l. He told me that there=E2=80=99s something like a Great Filter [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/96c30fc9-386a-4ad1-8b03-468c2b4a37e9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for Vertically Integra=
ted companies: =E2=80=9CAlmost all of the largest companies are vertically =
integrated. Almost none of the small ones are.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Robin Hanson dreamed up the Great Filter to address a mystery: where are th=
e aliens?=C2=A0
Humanity seems to have a bright future, i.e., a non-trivial chance of expan=
ding to fill the universe with lasting life. But the fact that space near u=
s seems dead now tells us that any given piece of dead matter faces an astr=
onomically low chance of begating such a future. There thus exists a great =
filter between death and expanding lasting life.
In his telling, as we discussed in the Deep Dive on Fuse [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/92537c65-8ed7-42ef-b84=
d-1210bb324c21?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], something must get in the way=
 between where we are now, on the cusp of universal expansion, and actually=
 realizing that potential to expand. Maybe it=E2=80=99s climate change. May=
be it=E2=80=99s nuclear war. Maybe it=E2=80=99s global pandemic.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
There are a number of reasons a civilization might not make the leap from c=
omputers, rockets, and nuclear power to intergalactic travel. Better unders=
tanding them may help us pass through the Great Filter and out into the uni=
verse.=C2=A0
Similarly, there are many reasons a Vertical Integrator may not make it fro=
m small, complex, wildly ambitious startup to large, dominant company. Unde=
rstanding them may help companies pass through that Great Filter of their o=
wn.=C2=A0
So in the third of our four-part series on Vertical Integrators, we=E2=80=
=99ll dig into what makes them so challenging.=C2=A0
While the specific difficulties faced by modern Vertical Integrators are mo=
re numerous than the companies themselves, there are seven categories that =
I want to focus on:=C2=A0
It requires building at least two companies: software and hardware.=C2=A0
Hardware by itself is just really hard.=C2=A0
Incumbents are good at what they do and have advantages.=C2=A0
Figuring out the right level of integration is not obvious.=C2=A0
You can=E2=80=99t pivot nearly as easily.=C2=A0
Something better might come along.=C2=A0
Getting to revenue takes a lot of money.=C2=A0
Building at Least Two Companies
The first thing about building a modern Vertical Integrator is that you hav=
e to build at least two companies: software and hardware. This sounds relat=
ively simple =E2=80=93 every company uses software nowadays =E2=80=93 but i=
t=E2=80=99s not.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a paradox in building a Vertical Integrator: software lets =
you build entirely new systems, but you can=E2=80=99t just sell the softwar=
e because there are no customers other than yourself who operate the same s=
ystem, so you need to build the hardware and do the whole thing yourself.=
=C2=A0
The idea of vertically integrating hardware and software is not new or nove=
l. Apple has been doing it since at least 1984, when the company launched t=
he Macintosh with the graphical operating system that was the predecessor t=
o MacOS.=C2=A0
Forty years later, Apple is the world=E2=80=99s most valuable company, with=
 a $3.3 trillion market cap. Yesterday, it announced iPhone 16, which deepl=
y integrates AI into the hardware and gives the company a big advantage in =
personal AI agents. The benefits of hardware-software integration are not a=
 big secret.
What=E2=80=99s funny, though, is that with all of those years of developmen=
t, all that money, all of Apple=E2=80=99s talent, and all of that integrati=
on, Apple=E2=80=99s software still kind of sucks.=C2=A0
Maybe that=E2=80=99s unfair, the software is OK. Open up your phone real qu=
ick though. Do you use Apple Calendar, Apple Mail, Apple Stocks, or Apple M=
aps, or an alternative built by the millions of developers throughout the r=
est of the world? Do you use Apple Music or Spotify? Open your computer. Do=
 you use Keynote, Pages, or Numbers, or an alternative product. If you use =
Numbers instead of Excel [ https://substack.com/redirect/6e5ce0df-b69d-4791=
-b2bb-362c0ba0a09b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], I would love to hear from you.=C2=A0
Of course, Apple wins either way. It charges 30% of all sales through the A=
pp Store. But the fact that Apple makes the world=E2=80=99s best hardware b=
ut isn=E2=80=99t the best in the world at making the software that runs on =
that hardware shows a few things.=C2=A0
First, hardware and software require different skills, and even different D=
NA. It=E2=80=99s hard for a software company to be a hardware company, and =
vice versa.=C2=A0
Second, no matter how good you are at software, chances are someone out the=
re can build software better than you can. If you=E2=80=99re building softw=
are for your very specific need, you=E2=80=99re probably not using the best=
 software you could be using.=C2=A0
Third, even if you=E2=80=99re really good at both software and hardware, ke=
eping the two in sync is a hard problem. Sometimes the software team moves =
faster, others the hardware team leaps ahead. Software has to run well on m=
any generations of hardware, which forces trade-offs.=C2=A0
To keep it simple, we=E2=80=99re just talking about two things: hardware an=
d software. In reality, it=E2=80=99s more complex than that. Anil suggested=
 that one of the reasons small vertically integrated companies don=E2=80=99=
t pass through the Great Filter is that it=E2=80=99s unnatural for small co=
mpanies to have 15 departments, to think about, excel at, and balance 15 di=
fferent things at the same time. It goes against all startup advice, which =
suggests becoming excellent at one thing.=C2=A0
Plus, dependencies and relationships scale quadratically. Fifteen departmen=
ts means 105 connections between departments. It gets messy quickly.=C2=A0
In When to Dig a Moat [ https://substack.com/redirect/3cce6b29-9494-4054-9b=
b7-0305e03fb503?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], we discussed the idea that startups=E2=80=99 advantages are unce=
rtainty and speed. They need to move quickly to build a product and dig moa=
ts before competitors have the time to react.=C2=A0
Adding so much complexity while there=E2=80=99s so much uncertainty often l=
eaves you with a dangerous combination of uncertainty and lethargy. This co=
mbo seems to be one of the main contributing factors to Katerra=E2=80=99s d=
emise. The company didn=E2=80=99t have a well thought out strategy [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/da1aee62-c7c9-47e5-91f0-51b63f06fd69?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], so it executed in a=
 number of directions without gaining forward momentum.=C2=A0
Katerra offered ten building types (like garden apartments or industrial bu=
ildings with CLT homes) and twelve building systems (like the prefab bathro=
om kit or CLT facade system), and built three software systems for construc=
tion management, design automation, and tenant management.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIdeally, early stage product development involves rapid iteration =
and prototyping, to figure out what needs to be built as quickly as possibl=
e,=E2=80=9D Potter wrote. =E2=80=9CBut the pace of product development at K=
aterra always felt sluggish.=E2=80=9D
Katerra tried to do too much, too soon. It went slow when it should have be=
en going fast. Maybe the right amount of functions to vertically integrate =
at the beginning is as simple as this: as many as you can without slowing d=
own the pace of iteration until you have a product that customers want to b=
uy at a price they=E2=80=99re willing to pay. =C2=A0
Getting it right isn=E2=80=99t impossible. SpaceX and Tesla have done it, e=
ven if there have been bumps along the way, Anduril, Meter, and others seem=
 to be doing it now, and Apple has been doing it for a long time.=C2=A0
In the beginning, it takes exceptional founders with a clear vision who can=
 keep the whole thing straight in their heads and communicate it crisply to=
 a growing team.
The good news from the Apple story is that if you can do both hardware and =
software at a certain level, the integration of the two creates a product t=
hat=E2=80=99s hard to beat. Apple is excellent at hardware, pretty good at =
software, and by integration both, has created an unmatched experience and =
the world=E2=80=99s most profitable product. During yesterday=E2=80=99s iPh=
one event, Craig said that Apple Intelligence =E2=80=9Cis only possible bec=
ause of our integration between hardware and software.=E2=80=9D
There=E2=80=99s actually more good news on the software-hardware integratio=
n front if you get it right, but I=E2=80=99ll save that for Part IV. This p=
art is about the challenges.=C2=A0
And there aren=E2=80=99t many things harder for startups than building hard=
ware.=C2=A0
Hardware is Really Hard
This point is so well-appreciated that I won=E2=80=99t spend much time on i=
t here: hardware is hard.=C2=A0
Hardware must obey the laws of physics. It also relies on complex and often=
 global supply chains, in which any one link can snap and bottleneck the en=
tire process. Iteration cycles are long. Upfront costs are high. You can=E2=
=80=99t build a hardware company on your laptop: you need machines and mate=
rials. Depending on what you=E2=80=99re building, operating in the physical=
 world will mean interacting with regulations and regulators that dramatica=
lly slow down or block what you=E2=80=99re doing. It=E2=80=99s usually for =
good reason =E2=80=93 you don=E2=80=99t want your hardware blowing up or fa=
lling from the sky =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s still an issue. In some cases=
, like nuclear, dealing with regulators takes years, at least tens of milli=
ons of dollars, and challenging uncertainty.=C2=A0
If you can figure all of that out, and get a product that works at small sc=
ale, you then need to scale manufacturing. Elon Musk went on Joe Rogan last=
 year, and the thing I remember most is how many times he said just how har=
d scaling manufacturing is:=C2=A0
Getting from nothing to something is hard, expensive, and uncertain. Gettin=
g from something to a lot of things, at a cost that=E2=80=99s competitive, =
is harder, more expensive, and if not more uncertain, then at least more gr=
ueling.=C2=A0
Sunil at Meter said that this is actually one of the hardest things about b=
uilding a Vertical Integrator:=C2=A0
Non-vertically integrated companies can say we=E2=80=99ve solved a thing an=
d move on. That=E2=80=99s not possible with vertically integrated companies=
=2E Every time you solve something,=20=
you=E2=80=99ve just bought a little time=20=
before you need to solve it again at the next level of scale.=C2=A0
As you=E2=80=99re scaling up, you need to solve everything from components =
to circuit design to supply chain to production every nine months.
In practice, that=E2=80=99s even harder than it sounds, because people like=
 working on new problems, not solving the same old ones over and over. You =
need to re-orient teams to understand that scale is the new problem and get=
 them so excited about mastering it that they don=E2=80=99t slow down, get =
out of sync, and make costly mistakes.=C2=A0
All of that is really hard for new companies to figure out. Worse, the comp=
anies you=E2=80=99re competing against have been doing all of that for a ve=
ry long time.=C2=A0
Strong Incumbents
A mistake that people in tech make, that I certainly make, is believing tha=
t imcumbents are incompetent sitting ducks, blissfully unaware of technolog=
y and unprepared for what=E2=80=99s going to hit them once startups figure =
out a new and better way of doing the thing they=E2=80=99ve always done.=C2=
=A0
Certainly, many incumbents have issues. We=E2=80=99ve beaten up on Boeing p=
lenty, but more generally, as Carlota Perez pointed out, incumbents are ent=
renched in a techno-economic paradigm that=E2=80=99s worked really well for=
 them and can be slow to adopt new technologies.=C2=A0
At the same time, however, these companies have been around for a very long=
 time and have gone through cycle after cycle to produce their products as =
efficiently and at as low a cost as possible. They often own the pieces of =
their supply chains that give them the biggest advantages, have built out n=
etworks of modular suppliers that depend on their business for the rest, ha=
ve tremendous amounts of information, enjoy both contracts and relationship=
s with the biggest customers in their industries, have even written the leg=
islation that governs them in a way that makes it especially difficult for =
new entrants to compete on equal footing, and employ thousands of people in=
 states across the country, which gives them sway with lawmakers.=C2=A0
Over the past couple of months, I=E2=80=99ve read or re-read Henry Ford=E2=
=80=99s My Life and Work [ https://substack.com/redirect/d2fab58f-36ce-4c3f=
-abb5-2520ba1d28ba?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], Kochland [ https://substack.com/redirect/1b9dee10-b1b5-4315-a=
139-1f6c5e528302?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] (the history of Koch Industries), Cable Cowboy [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/f1063e4f-fb0d-4e98-8d3d-c7f3e5d712b7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (the biography of TCI/Liberty=
 Media founder John Malone), and The Prize [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
03359448-1bdc-43a6-b754-c7af7e75a8cc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (the history of oil and its biggest companie=
s). I would recommend reading them and other industry-relevant company hist=
ories to anyone looking to build or invest in Vertical Integrators to give =
yourself an appreciation for just how sharp these companies and their leade=
rs are.=C2=A0
Incumbents will go to great lengths to protect what=E2=80=99s theirs and ha=
ve the resources to do so. Building versions of what they=E2=80=99ve built =
that are slightly better on one dimension won=E2=80=99t win. Even a slightl=
y cheaper product won=E2=80=99t win =E2=80=93 they can lower prices and sus=
tain losses to bleed you out.=C2=A0
These companies have mastered the last Techno-Economic Paradigm. Your only =
shot is building something radically better with the tools of the new one b=
ased on a prediction about where the market is going and then iterating lik=
e hell to a scaled solution before they adjust and catch up.=C2=A0
Just how long you have until they adjust and catch up depends on the specif=
ic incumbent and their circumstances. Building a Vertical Integrator in a s=
pace full of incumbents requires an incredibly deep understanding of each o=
f their strategies before even deciding to jump in.=C2=A0
What are they focused on? Have they made commitments to certain architectur=
es that will be hard to get out of? Have they promised investors that they=
=E2=80=99ll move in a direction that takes them away from the prize you=E2=
=80=99re pursuing? How strong is their team? Are star employees leaving?=C2=
=A0
You can=E2=80=99t assume your competitors are idiots, but you can make a ve=
ry educated guess about whether they=E2=80=99re in a position to shift thei=
r resources in your new and better direction, and do whatever you can to co=
unter-position [ https://substack.com/redirect/97dc494f-2810-4ad4-a4bd-cbd1=
23d4807f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] yourself against them.
Anduril [ https://substack.com/redirect/3944af58-60d1-4845-ae92-7eb8ea7c255=
8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], for=
 example, takes risk on its own balance sheet to develop programs that it b=
elieves the DoD will buy in the near-future so that it=E2=80=99s in the pos=
ition to win those contracts against Primes that operate on a cost-plus mod=
el and therefore need to wait until there=E2=80=99s a contract to begin dev=
elopment.=C2=A0
But in the beginning, while you=E2=80=99re still operating with the advanta=
ge of uncertainty, the best you can do is form hypotheses, make predictions=
, and sprint.=C2=A0
Those predictions are hard to get right. Building a new system out of a num=
ber of very new technologies and inputs is harder than it sounds on paper.=
=C2=A0
The Right Level of Integration is Not Obvious
I started Part II with a story about Hadrian [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/4cf0d393-4d2a-4458-ad6e-3f58716e69fb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to make one point: software alone isn=E2=
=80=99t usually enough to solve the problem. What I didn=E2=80=99t cover is=
 that too much vertical integration, too soon, is an issue, too.=C2=A0
In that Deep Dive on Hadrian [ https://substack.com/redirect/4cf0d393-4d2a-=
4458-ad6e-3f58716e69fb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I highlighted that two of the company=E2=80=99s lead inve=
stors, Lux and Founders Fund, had previously backed a company trying to aut=
omate parts manufacturing: Plethora. The company, founded in 2013 to build =
the factory of the future by creating =E2=80=9Ca manufacturing system that =
turns customer designs into custom parts using robotics and advanced softwa=
re that we=E2=80=99ve developed in-house,=E2=80=9D failed.=C2=A0
There were three lessons from Plethora=E2=80=99s failure, according to inve=
stors and former employees:
They tried to do everything in software, cutting the humans out of the loop=
, which meant years of wasted time trying to solve =E2=80=9Chobby problems=
=E2=80=9D that humans could easily do.
The offering was too broad =E2=80=93 from prototypes to parts, different ma=
terials, different shapes, high-end and low-end, not precision-focused =E2=
=80=93 Plethora wanted to do everything.
It was a little too early, both in terms of customer demand for high-precis=
ion parts and in terms of the financing market for a business like this.
In short: Plethora tried to do too much, too soon, too early.=C2=A0
This rhymes with Katerra=E2=80=99s failure: too much, too soon, if not too =
early (people will always want cheaper houses).=C2=A0
Katerra also likely vertically integrated too deep into the materials suppl=
y chain. As Potter points out, the company invested ~$100 million into a Cr=
oss-Laminated Timber (CLT) factory that could produce ~10% of the world=E2=
=80=99s supply of CLT. In addition to being a big investment of limited res=
ources, it locked the company into a product that he said ended up getting =
cut out of plans in value engineering too often because it=E2=80=99s an exp=
ensive material.=C2=A0
A lesson might be this: vertically integrate to whatever level will give yo=
u the best product at the lowest cost (lower than legacy alternatives) befo=
re integrating further with scale.=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s about a billion times easier to write than it is to do.=
=C2=A0
Plethora likely believed that fully automating would let it produce the bes=
t products at the lowest cost before running into all of the challenges of =
actually building a fully automated manufacturing process. Katerra likely b=
elieved that its breadth and ownership of the supply chain were these inter=
linked things that, if everything went just right, would allow it to achiev=
e the scale required to build the best product at the lowest cost.=20
There=E2=80=99s probably no shortcut but experimentation at fast iteration =
speed. You need to form a hypothesis, try it out, and adjust. The problem i=
s, unlike software, the =E2=80=9Cminimum viable product=E2=80=9D requires a=
 ton of commitment in one direction.=C2=A0
Pivoting is Not Easy
In other words, pivoting is not easy. The first-of-a-kind (FOAK) product or=
 plant will never run at the costs that the nth product or plant will, and =
the only way to figure out whether the benefits you think you=E2=80=99ll ge=
t from scale are real is to actually build the thing, and then scale.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
The other four points on why Vertical Integrators are so hard to build are =
magnified by the fact that you can=E2=80=99t simply change course once you =
run into issues.=C2=A0
Of course, you can iterate. You have to iterate. SpaceX is famously OK with=
 blowing up rockets in order to learn and improve. But even SpaceX didn=E2=
=80=99t decide that it would start building space elevators instead of rock=
ets, or even that it would stop building reusable rockets in favor of some =
new approach after its first few rockets blew up. It iterated towards the s=
ame product vision.=C2=A0
Traditional software is full of stories of companies that pivoted from one =
thing to another. Instagram was Blendr. Slack was Tiny Speck. Twitter was O=
deo. Pinterest was Tote. YouTube was a video dating site. Shopify was a sno=
wboarding ecommerce store.=C2=A0
Such dramatic pivots are harder in hardware, and practically impossible wit=
h Vertical Integrators. It takes too much upfront capital invested in one d=
irection and too much specialized talent hired with one system in mind to s=
imply switch course when something isn=E2=80=99t working.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s an ongoing debate about whether strategy matters for startu=
ps. I picked my side in In Defense of Strategy [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/da1aee62-c7c9-47e5-91f0-51b63f06fd69?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but I can squint and see that for certa=
in software products, just getting the very best developers around the tabl=
e and executing like mad until you find product-market fit with something. =
I don=E2=80=99t think that approach is at all feasible for Vertical Integra=
tors.=C2=A0
A sound strategy is critical for Vertical Integrators. You need to work out=
 as much as you possibly can on paper before enshrining it in metal. As a g=
reat example, check out the Base Power Company Deep Dive [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/bff36cf0-d0d1-4fae-a63=
1-a774772bfbc5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Zach and Justin banged on the=
 idea as many ways as they could, and talked to as many people as they coul=
d, before expanding the team and putting a product into market.=C2=A0=C2=A0
If you get it wrong, it might be up to the next company to get it right. Th=
is is another reason for =E2=80=9CWhy Now?=E2=80=9D for Vertical Integrator=
s that we didn=E2=80=99t cover in Part II. If each individual Vertical Inte=
grator is limited in its ability to pivot, a new wave of entrepreneurs can =
incorporate the lessons from previous attempts into fresh approaches. Pleth=
ora informed Hadrian. Katerra informed Cuby [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/0a141410-d4cc-475a-a398-9028ad1d4d4f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (on which more soon). Previous entrepreneur=
s have tried and failed to do build companies that sound similar in their g=
oals to today=E2=80=99s Vertical Integrators.=C2=A0
While it=E2=80=99s easy to look at failed attempts as proof positive that =
=E2=80=9Cthis will never work,=E2=80=9D I think one of the best signals tha=
t a category is investable is a previous failure with clear and actionable =
lessons.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s small comfort for the companies that took the arrows, burnin=
g years to learn expensive and valuable lessons.=C2=A0
But say you don=E2=80=99t need to pivot. You have something that works, tha=
t scales, and that seems to be significantly better than incumbents can off=
er.=C2=A0
You=E2=80=99re not done yet.=C2=A0
Something Better Might Come Along
This might be the most pernicious of the challenges.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Imagine doing all of the hard things required to get a Vertical Integrator =
to enough scale to get product quality and costs to a competitive level and=
 then having a new entrant come along, using your hard-earned lessons and s=
ome newfangled technology to promise something even better or cheaper than =
what you=E2=80=99ve built.=C2=A0
With the pace of technological advancement happening right now, that=E2=80=
=99s always a very real possibility.=C2=A0
One of my favorite questions to ask founders is, =E2=80=9CWhat sci-fi techn=
ology are you most worried about obsoleting your approach?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s an absurd question on its face, but sci-fi has a way of coming=
 true [ https://substack.com/redirect/eb5707bf-a43c-4c93-993d-5a13f51c982b?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and t=
he absurdity helps me get to the question I=E2=80=99m going for, which is: =
how close to the best possible approach is what you=E2=80=99re planning to =
build.=C2=A0
As a non-Vertical Integrator example, think about building an AI product. I=
f your answer is =E2=80=9CIf GPT-5 is as much of an improvement over GPT-4 =
as GPT-4 was over GPT-3, we=E2=80=99re in trouble,=E2=80=9D then you=E2=80=
=99re probably in trouble. If it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CAGI might be an issue i=
f it=E2=80=99s able to do everything in the world,=E2=80=9D you might be sa=
fer.=C2=A0
In energy, if the answer is =E2=80=9CNikola Tesla=E2=80=99s free energy [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/3348a13f-501b-4caa-896b-ae13b3a140b6?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=E2=80=9D then =
that=E2=80=99s just a chance you have to take.=C2=A0
If it=E2=80=99s, =E2=80=9CCommercial fusion power would blow us out,=E2=80=
=9D then you can underwrite the company based on how long you expect commer=
cial fusion to get to grid-scale generation. If it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CIf pe=
ople actually start bringing nuclear reactors down the cost curve, that wou=
ld be a problem,=E2=80=9D then you might have a real problem.=C2=A0
The answers usually aren=E2=80=99t that black-and-white. In some cases, the=
re may be competing approaches, each pursued by equally smart people with e=
qually well-thought-out strategies and roughly equal abilities to execute. =
In some cases, those two companies may end up owning different parts of the=
 market =E2=80=93 one approach might work slightly better for one use, and =
the other for another. Sometimes, it=E2=80=99s just going to be a race: who=
 can get their product into customers=E2=80=99 hands quickly enough to begi=
n to scale and then get to scale quickly enough to underprice their competi=
tor soonest.=C2=A0
The fact that there may be a better approach unlocked by one or two more te=
chnological advances is just something to be aware of, and to take advantag=
e of if possible. This is one of the reasons that I prefer investing in Ver=
tical Integrators over Deep Tech companies as defined in Part I [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/d31bc5aa-752e-49ba-b3ce-44d9cfc72342?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. A Vertical Integrator =
should be in a position to incorporate the new and better technology into t=
heir system if and when it comes to fruition.=C2=A0
And ideally, if they=E2=80=99ve executed well, they=E2=80=99ll have enough =
momentum, scale, and capital to make it even more difficult for the next co=
mpany to compete unless they have anything short of Tesla=E2=80=99s free en=
ergy machine.=C2=A0
Getting to Revenue Takes a Lot of Money
Building a Vertical Integrator is expensive. It requires hiring world-class=
 people with very specific skillsets across a variety of disciplines, buyin=
g machines and materials, hiring lawyers, and occasionally, blowing up very=
 expensive machines.=C2=A0
It can also take a long time to build a product that someone will buy. Wher=
eas a pre-seed software company can =E2=80=93 not always, see Figma, but ca=
n =E2=80=93 start generating revenue very quickly, there are plenty of Vert=
ical Integrators that raise their Series B without ever having earned a dol=
lar of revenue.=C2=A0
They need to convince venture capitalists to give them money based on their=
 idea and their experience, and then on the team that they are able to hire=
, and then on the progress that that team is making on building the complex=
 system that they=E2=80=99re trying to build, without the easy-to-evaluate =
=E2=80=9Crevenue go up=E2=80=9D hockey stick charts software companies at a=
 similar stage can rely on.=C2=A0
This isn=E2=80=99t always the case. Sometimes, Vertical Integrators can ear=
n money on an early, scaled-down version of their product. Sometimes, with =
enough capital and speed, Vertical Integrators can start earning revenue qu=
ickly. As I mentioned in Part II, Hadrian is on track for $30 million in re=
venue this year as a three-year-old company.=C2=A0Varda [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/38573afb-7d28-4a37-88d8-d0b5b5be339e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] set a goal to generate revenue =
within three years, and was executing on $60 million worth of DoD contracts=
 within that window. =20
Revenue or no revenue, fundraising can=E2=80=99t be an afterthought for Ver=
tical Integrators. It needs to be baked into the strategy from day one.=20
Founders need to understand what it will take to get to the point at which =
their company can count on debt and project financing to scale, and then co=
nvince venture capitalists to fund them to that point, even though they may=
 have very little revenue to show for it in the interim.=C2=A0
Vertical Integrators face a well-known =E2=80=9CValley of Death=E2=80=9D be=
tween those exciting early days when the idea exists on paper and in the he=
ads of a fresh, world-class team and when the reality of executing on the p=
lan has set in before real revenue has come in. Many companies overcome a n=
umber of early challenges only to run out of the money they need to bring t=
he product to customers.=20
As I touched on in Part II [ https://substack.com/redirect/eedd8a4f-4990-4d=
b4-95ab-3512c27cd9ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ], though, I actually think that venture capital is lining up =
perfectly to provide the equity capital these businesses will need, and tha=
t Vertical Integrators are less dilutive than people expect because they ca=
n tap non-dilutive sources of funding including grants, debt, government co=
ntracts, project financing, and of course, revenue. And getting most of the=
 investors willing to fund this kind of all-or-nothing bet on your side mea=
ns that it=E2=80=99s even harder for someone new to come in and knock you o=
ff in-flight.=C2=A0
This financing challenge is, like all of the others, one that flips to an a=
dvantage if you can overcome it.=C2=A0
Luckily, very, very, very hard is not the same thing as impossible. It just=
 takes very talented people executing relentlessly to show the difference.=
=C2=A0
Hard but Not Impossible
Alright, have I scared you enough for one day?=C2=A0
These are just seven categories of challenges. We didn=E2=80=99t even touch=
 on some big ones, like regulation or logistics, that may be more applicabl=
e to some Vertical Integrators more than others. And I suspect that if ther=
e are people out there reading this who are actually building Vertical Inte=
grators instead of just writing about them, they=E2=80=99ll say that I actu=
ally missed a lot of the really hard things, or the little annoyances that =
really gum up the works in the day-to-day.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve been through this myself. Breather was vertically integrated: =
we leased office spaces, undertook construction and design, even produced o=
ur own furniture, built an app that let customers book and access spaces, a=
nd backstage software that helped our team manage operations, and ran an in=
-house team of Operations Associates who cleaned and maintained our spaces =
after hundreds of bookings across 500 spaces in ten cities across the world=
=2E=C2=A0
Some of the little things I remember include showing up to a building to se=
t up a new space only to realize that our moving company didn=E2=80=99t hav=
e the right insurance and getting sent back to the warehouse, watching Back=
stage in horror as an operations associate got tied up in one location and =
miss a job at another, meaning that customers walked into a space that the =
previous ones had left a mess, and fielding angry phone calls from customer=
s who were locked out of a space before an important meeting because the ap=
p went down.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not just the big, splashy things that you need to get right, b=
ut all of the little details. The surface area for problems is massive, and=
 in an integrated system, a small problem in one place can have big consequ=
ences on the whole thing.=C2=A0
And yet=E2=80=A6 a lot of very smart, talented people who are eyes-wide-ope=
n about the challenges and have plenty of opportunities to do something eas=
ier choose to build Vertical Integrators.=C2=A0
Theodore Roosevelt said that =E2=80=9CNothing in the world is worth doing u=
nless it means effort, pain, difficulty.=E2=80=9D He might have been talkin=
g about Vertical Integrators: during his presidency, U.S. Steel was formed,=
 Ford was born, and Standard Oil, General Electric, and Westinghouse Electr=
ic grew substantially.=C2=A0
Today=E2=80=99s Vertical Integrators face even greater challenges in many w=
ays than those faced by the Second Industrial Revolution=E2=80=99s industri=
alists. Instead of a wide-open and fragmented landscape, they face competit=
ion from well-resourced, powerful, and experienced incumbents. Instead of j=
ust building hardware, they need to build hardware and software.=20
Against the odds, though, some of them even make it through the Great Filte=
r to build big, important companies. On the other side, assuming you picked=
 the right problem to solve, the outcome is proportional to the difficulty =
it took to get there.=C2=A0
Next week, in the fourth and final installment of our Vertical Integrators =
series, we=E2=80=99ll talk about what it takes to pull it off, the advantag=
es to vertical integration that lie on the other side of the challenges we =
discussed today, and the size of the prize for pulling off the near-impossi=
ble.
Thanks to Anil, Sunil, and Sep for your insights, and to Claude for editing=
=2E=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

