, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Sunil a=
t Meter said that this is actually one of the hardest things about building=
 a Vertical Integrator:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px soli=
d #0c2427; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;=
"><em>Non-vertically integrated companies can say we&#8217;ve solved a thin=
g and move on. That&#8217;s not possible with vertically integrated compani=
es. Every time you solve something, you&#8217;ve just bought a little time =
before you need to solve it again at the next level of scale.&#160;</em></p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>As you&#8217;re scaling up, you n=
eed to solve everything from components to circuit design to supply chain t=
o production every nine months.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In p=
ractice, that&#8217;s even harder than it sounds, because people like worki=
ng on new problems, not solving the same old ones over and over. You need t=
o re-orient teams to understand that scale is the new problem and get them =
so excited about mastering it that they don&#8217;t slow down, get out of s=
ync, and make costly mistakes.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">All of that is re=
ally hard for new companies to figure out. Worse, the companies you&#8217;r=
e competing against have been doing all of that for a very long time.&#160;=
</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" style=3D"--highlight-bg: rgba(var(--co=
